4_38	0.05555555555555555	The man at the center of the 1973 case, Samuel Bronston, a movie producer, filed for bankruptcy and was asked in testimony in his bankruptcy case whether he had ever had Swiss bank accounts.
4_39	0.0	Bronston's answer was: ``The company had an account there for about six months, in Zurich''.
4_40	0.0	In fact, he once had $180,000 in an account in Geneva that he did not mention.
4_41	0.0	Bronston was later found guilty of perjury.
4_42	0.8	The Supreme Court reversed the conviction.
4_43	0.16666666666666666	The high court said that even if Bronston's answers ``were shrewdly calculated to evade'' it was the lawyer's responsibility to bring the witness ``back to the mark, to flush out the whole truth''.
4_44	0.0	Some critics of that ruling say it added momentum to the rampant telling of half-truths in the courts.
