18_1	0.0	The 50-year-old papers are thought to reveal key information about one of the most disputed episodes of the era.
18_2	0.0625	Hiss, a key government aide, was accused of spying for the Soviet Union in 1948, but was tried on perjury charges when the statute of limitations for espionage expired.
18_3	0.2727272727272727	He was sent to prison for three years in 1951 and died in 1996 at age 92, still maintaining his innocence.
18_4	0.0	``Access to such information inevitably enhances the accuracy of history and undermines the false conspiracy theories and revisionism that tend to arise when information remains secret,'' U.S.
18_5	0.0	District Judge Peter Leisure said in his ruling Thursday.
